.TH "nanddev_bbt_set_block_status" 9 "nanddev_bbt_set_block_status" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
nanddev_bbt_set_block_status \- Update the status of an eraseblock in the in-memory BBT
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" nanddev_bbt_set_block_status
.BI "(struct nand_device *nand "  ","
.BI "unsigned int entry "  ","
.BI "enum nand_bbt_block_status status "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "nand" 12
nand device
.IP "entry" 12
the BBT entry to update
.IP "status" 12
the new status
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Update an entry of the in-memory BBT. If you want to push the updated BBT
the NAND you should call \fBnanddev_bbt_update\fP.
.SH "RETURN"
0 in case of success or -ERANGE if \fIentry\fP is bigger than the BBT
size.
